Ok, this patchset has been long awaited, and is GREAT to see.  I want to make that clear;  If it feels like I'm picking on it in the comments, it's mostly because I would expect this to be used all over bmcweb, and I want to make sure we get some design patters well understood before we go and replicate it a gazillion times throughout the codebase.
Very nice
Thanks! Totally understand and the feedback is greatly appreciated.

NIT: 
please move to line 385, to keep the redfish-core/lib/ut test to together and in alphabetical order
Done.

I realize this is the first patch, and only doing a portion.  Considering that this is going to turn essentially every handler method we have into a template, I worry a little what that does to compile times and bug readability.  Is there any way to avoid the template with composition or <gasps> inheritance?

This is a very cool way to mock arguments. I have never seen it before.

But it would be easier to read if you could pass in a mockSdbus that inherits and overrides sdbusplus::asio::connection. Then forgo the templateing.

The inheritance way is how I wish I could have done it from the start. Unfortunately, all the methods in sdbusplus::asio::connection are non-virtual, so MockSdbusConnection can't override them.

I was messing around with it today and I can't really get around this issue without going in and creating an interface for sdbusplus::asio::connection. I'm also not a huge fan of the templating within log_services.hpp, but I think it's unavoidable without significant changes to sdbusplus::asio::connection (and anything that uses it).

I'd appreciate any suggestions though!

> The inheritance way is how I wish I could have done it from the start. Unfortunately, all the methods in sdbusplus::asio::connection are non-virtual, so MockSdbusConnection can't override them.

Composition is still an 

> 
> I was messing around with it today and I can't really get around this issue without going in and creating an interface for sdbusplus::asio::connection.

Considering we only explicitly call the name sdbusplus::asio::connection in one place (where we declare the global and where we init it in main) we should be able to invent a new interface pointer there, right?

> I'm also not a huge fan of the templating within log_services.hpp, but I think it's unavoidable without significant changes to sdbusplus::asio::connection (and anything that uses it).

OpenBMC has control over sdbusplus::asio::connection, so if we do need to make significant changes, we certainly can.

> 
> I'd appreciate any suggestions though!

Have you attempted a composition based approach?  When I played around with it earlier, it seemed to work.

Nit, unless this function needs to take ownership of bus in some way (which it doesn't look like it does) this should be passed by a reference, not a pointer.  This helps in that we don't have to nullptr check it inside every handler, and it helps users know that it's just using the bus, rather than "owning" the bus.

That makes sense. Updated.

Also changed the type and argument names to better reflect what this actually is.
This is just using the default systembus?  Don't we want to avoid that entirely in a unit test?  (I'm surprised this pointer is even filled in in a unit test context).
That pointer is never used in this test, which is why this doesn't fail. Pretty sure it's not filled in, but I've changed it to be the mock object since that seems more appropriate for a test.
Isn't this the default?
Yeah, you're right. Removed the unnecessary lines throughout the test.
I was supposed to review LogService related changes, please add me to the reviewer list. Especially these are google changes. Thanks!

Last known public discussion on D-bus mocking for bmcweb unit tests suggests using mocks from sdbusplus as opposed to bmcweb: https://discord.com/channels/775381525260664832/1003720114400661576.

There was also an earlier project (abandoned due to inactivity) for providing D-Bus mocking across OpenBMC, though its initial stated goal was integration testing of entire daemons as opposed to unit testing: https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/docs/+/37378

This is something I want to do as well, to mock the systemConnection. However, I agree that template is not the best solution.

Given that now systemConnection is an extern variable, can we just point it to a mock object in the unit test binary?
Please use <> for system headers.
Please add a Namespace to the tests, like what the other unit tests do.
fully qualifying using declarations?
